@node intro "Introduction"
@{fg shine}
 >>> INTRODUCTION
@{fg text}
 @{"MacFind" link mfind} is a program for searching your hard drive (or CD-ROMs) for files.
 Surely you must have had times when you wondered exactly where a certain
 file is?  Well, wonder no more!  :)

 Okay, there are literally dozens of file-finding programs out there on
 Aminet, so why should you use @{b}MacFind@{ub} instead of those?  Well, hopefully
 because it's the most user-friendly.  I've had a play with most of those
 other programs and they all do one thing: suck.  :)  How I wished that a
 program would search for files in the classic way that the Macintosh does!

 There's an old saying: @{i}If you want something done, do it yourself@{ui}.  So I
 did, and @{b}MacFind@{ub} was born.

 It lets you search for files with the brilliant user-friendliness that Mac
 users have enjoyed for soooooo long.  Basically, you tell @{b}MacFind@{ub} in plain
 English what the file is, and where to start looking, and then you sit back
 and relax while it hunts it down like a dog.

 Other reasons to use @{b}MacFind@{ub} instead of something else?  Take your pick:

  · Doesn't use MUI!
  · Doesn't use the CLI (this is user-friendly, remember?)
  · Doesn't need other external libraries (eg: BGUI.library)
  · Allows search data to be entered in plain English
  · Optionally creates a text file of all search matches
  · It's totally FREE and no payment is required!

 Weigh up those benefits with other search engines, and I'm sure you'll
 agree that they pale in comparison.  Enjoy!  :)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node requi "Requirements"
@{fg shine}
 >>> REQUIREMENTS
@{fg text}
 @{"MacFind" link mfind} requires the following items to run:

  · Any Amiga running Workbench 2.04 or higher
  · ReqTools.library (click @{"here" link rtool} for more info)

 No further requirements for @{b}MacFind@{ub} are necessary.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node amiga "Compatibility"
@{fg shine}
 >>> COMPATIBILITY
@{fg text}
 Firstly, I'll assume you've read the @{"requirements" link requi} section...?  Good!

 Okay, @{"MacFind" link mfind} has only been tested on one Amiga, since that's all the
 the @{"author" link autho} has access to.  It has the following configuration:

  · Amiga 1200, Workbench 3.1, AGA Chipset, 68020, 2 MB Chip, 4 MB Fast.

 Thus, the author can absolutely, positively, @{i}guarantee without question@{ui}
 that @{b}MacFind@{ub} will run on such a system.  :)

 Anyway, if the program crashes on @{i}your@{ui} system, try the following:

  · Ensure @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub} is installed on your @{i}original@{ui} Workbench disk.
  · Boot from your original Workbench disk.
  · Run the offending program.

 The program @{i}should@{ui} now run without hassle.  It @{i}does@{ui} on the author's Amiga,
 when he performs the same three steps as above.  If you @{i}still@{ui} encounter
 problems, then I'm afraid it's not due to the program, but definitely due
 to something else you have installed which is clashing with it.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node rtool "ReqTools.library"
@{fg shine}
 >>> WHAT THE HECK IS "REQTOOLS.LIBRARY" ?
@{fg text}
 @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub} is what you might consider a "system enhancer" for your
 Amiga.  Basically, it's a file that many programs use that enable them to
 provide "requesters" of all shapes and sizes.  In fact, it's so popular
 that you might already have it installed in your system!

 If you run @{"MacFind" link mfind} and get an error message saying that @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub}
 is not installed, then unfortunately you don't have it yet.  You'll have to
 download it from Aminet: its name is @{b}ReqToolsUsr.lha@{ub} and it's found in the
 @{b}util/libs@{ub} directory.  Install it as soon as possible, because a great deal
 of Amiga software makes use of it these days.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node mfind "Basic Usage"
@{fg shine}
 >>> BASIC USAGE OF MAC FIND
@{fg text}
 Double-click the @{b}MacFind@{ub} icon and a small window will open on the centre of
 the screen.  It resembles (partially) the Mac's @{b}Find@{ub} window, except that
 it's a bit more sophisticated.  If you read the window like a book, you'll
 notice in the top-half that it says:
@{i}
 Using <drive> as the path, find files whose <name> <includes> <match>.
@{ui}
 You can't get more plain English than that!  :)  The words in brackets are
 are what you can change to streamline your search.  This is how:
@{b}
 <drive>@{ub}
  This is the drive you want to search.  Just click the disk-gadget to the
  right of the word @{i}Using@{ui} and you'll be presented with a requester asking
  you to specify a drive and/or directory.  Alternatively, you can directly
  enter the device/path by clicking in the text box next to it.
@{b}
 <name>@{ub}
  This is a cycle-gadget that lets you search for files by name, size, date,
  or note (also known as comment).
@{b}
 <includes>@{ub}
  This is a powerful cycle-gadget that lets you @{i}really@{ui} get your hands dirty
  with your search!  :)  It cycles between these search types: @{b}Includes@{ub},
  @{b}Excludes@{ub}, @{b}Starts With@{ub}, @{b}Ends With@{ub}, @{b}Is < Than@{ub}, @{b}Is > Than@{ub}, @{b}Is@{ub}, @{b}Is Not@{ub}.
@{b}
 <match>@{ub}
  This is where you specify exactly @{i}what@{ui} you want to find.

 In the bottom-half of the window are 4 tick gadgets.  These are your search
 preference gadgets and can aid to your searches dramatically.  Here is an
 explanation of what each does:
@{b}
 Create A List Of Matches@{ub}
  If ticked, a text file will be created in RAM: called "MacFind.txt" that
  is a list of all matches found.  You can copy this list to somewhere
  permanent on your hard drive if desired, for later perusal.
@{b}
 View All Matches Found@{ub}
  If ticked, a full-screen window will open when the search begins, and all
  matches found will be listed in it.  This prevents the hassle of referring
  to the above-mentioned RAM: listing if that bothers you, especially if you
  know that only a small range of files (say 10-20) will be matched.  The
  window, unfortunately, can't be scrolled backwards, as this would increase
  memory usage due to the need for a buffer, as well as the fact that you
  can already choose to save a list in RAM: if that need arises.
@{b}
 Don't Stop At Each Match@{ub}
  If ticked, MacFind won't bother you with a "Match Found!" requester each
  time a match occurs.  However, this prevents the making of @{"aliases" link alias}...
@{b}
 Obey Case Sensitivity@{ub}
  If ticked, a match will @{i}only@{ui} be generated if the file's name or note is
  exactly the same case as the search data.

 Basically, all you do to perform a search is specify the type of search
 (name, size, date, note), followed by the path, and lastly the data to be
 found.  If you alter the path or data, a new search will begin immediately,
 saving you the hassle of clicking the @{b}Scan!@{ub} gadget.  If you alter the
 type or method of search, you will have to click @{b}Scan!@{ub} to initiate it.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node findn "Searching Names Or Notes"
@{fg shine}
 >>> SEARCHING NAMES OR NOTES
@{fg text}
 The explanations that follow assume that you have set the path to be
 searched and have selected one of the following eight search methods.
 These methods will now be explained.
@{b}
 Includes@{ub}
  Any file name/note that contains the match data is found.
@{b}
 Excludes@{ub}
  Any file name/note that doesn't contain the match data is found.
@{b}
 Starts With@{ub}
  Any file name/note that starts with the match data is found.
@{b}
 Ends With@{ub}
  Any file name/note that ends with the match data is found.
@{b}
 Is < Than@{ub}
  Any file name/note whose first letter is lower than the first letter of
  the match data is found.  This allows alphabetical searches.  Be aware
  that such searches are affected by case sensitivity.
@{b}
 Is > Than@{ub}
  Any file name/note whose first letter is higher than the first letter of
  the match data is found.  This allows alphabetical searches.  Be aware
  that such searches are affected by case sensitivity.
@{b}
 Is@{ub}
  Any file name/note that is exactly the same as the match data is found.
@{b}
 Is Not@{ub}
  Any file name/note that is not exactly the same as the match data is
  found.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node finds "Searching Sizes"
@{fg shine}
 >>> SEARCHING SIZES
@{fg text}
 The explanations that follow assume that you have set the path to be
 searched and have selected one of the following eight search methods.
 These methods will now be explained.
@{b}
 Includes@{ub}
  Any file size that contains the match size is found.  For example, if you
  searched for 136, then a file size of 9745136 would be found, but 9745
  would not.
@{b}
 Excludes@{ub}
  Any file size that doesn't contain the match data is found.  For example,
  if you searched for 136, then a file size of 9745 would be found, but
  9745136 would not.
@{b}
 Starts With@{ub}
  Any file size that starts with the match data is found.  For example, if
  you searched for 136, then a file size of 1369745 would be found, but
  9745136 would not.
@{b}
 Ends With@{ub}
  Any file size that ends with the match data is found.  For example, if you
  searched for 136, then a file size of 9745136 would be found, but 1369745
  would not.
@{b}
 Is < Than@{ub}
  Any file size that is lower than the match data value is found.
@{b}
 Is > Than@{ub}
  Any file size that is higher than the match data value is found.
@{b}
 Is@{ub}
  Any file size that is exactly the same as the match data value is found.
@{b}
 Is Not@{ub}
  Any file size that is not exactly the same as the match data value is
  found.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node findd "Searching Dates"
@{fg shine}
 >>> SEARCHING DATES
@{fg text}
 The explanations that follow assume that you have set the path to be
 searched and have selected one of the following eight search methods.
 These methods will now be explained.
@{b}
 Includes@{ub}
  Any file date that contains the match data is found.  For example, if you
  searched for 1997, then any file created in 1997 would be found.
@{b}
 Excludes@{ub}
  Any file date that doesn't contain the match data is found.  For example,
  if you searched for 1997, then any file not created in 1997 would be
  found.
@{b}
 Starts With@{ub}
  @{i}NOTE:@{ui} This option only checks for day matches, and not months or years.
  Any file date that starts with the match data is found.  For example, if
  you searched for 20, then any file created on the 20th of any month would
  be found.
@{b}
 Ends With@{ub}
  @{i}NOTE:@{ui} This option only checks for year matches, and not days or months.
  Any file date that ends with the match data is found.  For example, if you
  searched for 1997, then any file created in 1997 would be found.
@{b}
 Is < Than@{ub}
  @{i}NOTE:@{ui} A match format of dd/mm/yyyy @{i}must@{ui} be used for this option.
  Any file date that is lower than the match data is found.  For example, if
  you searched for 20/05/1997, then any file created before that date will
  be found.
@{b}
 Is > Than@{ub}
  @{i}NOTE:@{ui} A match format of dd/mm/yyyy @{i}must@{ui} be used for this option.
  Any file date that is higher than the match data is found.  For example,
  if you searched for 20/05/1997, then any file created after that date
  will be found.
@{b}
 Is@{ub}
  @{i}NOTE:@{ui} A match format of dd/mm/yyyy @{i}must@{ui} be used for this option.
  Any file date that is exactly the same as the match data is found.
@{b}
 Is Not@{ub}
  @{i}NOTE:@{ui} A match format of dd/mm/yyyy @{i}must@{ui} be used for this option.
  Any file date that is not exactly the same as the match data is found.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node alias "Making Aliases"
@{fg shine}
 >>> MAKING ALIASES
@{fg text}
 When a match is found, you may notice an option to make an alias for it.
 This option is only presented when the match is an @{i}executable@{ui} file, that
 is, a file that can be run from Workbench or the CLI.

 If you elect to make an alias for it, an icon will be created in the @{b}Ram
 Disk@{ub} with the name of the file.  This icon is the alias, and it works in
 the same way as the Macintosh's aliases.  If you open the Ram Disk and
 double-click the alias icon, the found file will be run as if you opened
 all the drawers to it and double-clicked it from there.  This saves a lot
 of time in running something that is hidden deep down in your hard drive.
 Even the ToolTypes of the original icon are supported; but... if the file
 requires CLI options then these unfortunately @{i}won't@{ui} be emulated.

 Aliases in the Ram Disk are obviously lost when you reboot or turn off your
 Amiga, so drag them to a convenient place on your hard drive if you wish to
 keep them for future use.  :)

 For an alias to work correctly, you need to have a program called @{b}WBRun@{ub}
 installed on your Amiga.  This consists of two files called @{b}WBRun@{ub} and
 @{b}param.library@{ub} which must be in @{b}SYS:C@{ub} and @{b}SYS:Libs@{ub} respectively.  If you
 don't already have these installed, you can double-click the @{b}Install WBRun@{ub}
 icon and they will be installed immediately for you.  In addition, you'll
 need to have a file called @{b}IconX@{ub} in your @{b}SYS:C@{ub} directory, but that should
 already be there because it's a part of Workbench.

 Anyway, once they're installed, you will be able to use aliases to your
 heart's content!  :)  One last note: If you ever want to know where the
 original file exists on your hard drive (that the alias represents), just
 click once on the alias and select @{b}Information@{ub} from the @{b}Icon@{ub} menu.  You'll
 see the original path and file name are stored in the @{b}Comment@{ub} box for your
 referral.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode

